It's National Seal Products Day! A Bill creating this national day was adopted by the House of Commons of the Government of Canada on May 5, 2017.
In Canada's North, seal harvesters, processors, artisans and Inuit produce some of the finest quality seal products in the world and contribute to Canada’s economy. Learn about this sustainable  economic activity and its social and cultural importance: http://ow.ly/40Ym30bS5DJ

Did you know that 75% of Inuit living in Nunavut speak Inuktitut as their mother tongue? Inuit languages in Nunavut can be written using roman orthography (the alphabet used in English) or using syllabics (an alphabet used for a number of Indigenous languages in Canada). Learn more about the language here: http://ow.ly/GfB630bS8T1 
#Inuit #IndigenousLanguages"

On Saturday, May 27, INAC is hosting a Family Science Day focused on water issues in Iqaluit, Nunavut. 

From 11:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m., learn about why and how water quality is monitored. (Suggested age for the lab is 10+)
From 2:00 p.m. to 4:00 p.m., enjoy a fun filled afternoon featuring short films and trivia. 

Both activities are free and will be held at the Nunavut Research Institute (Bldg 959).

caption_original: Muskoxen (named "omingmak" by the Inuit) are large, shaggy relatives of mountain sheep and mountain goats. Their thick layer of insulating underwool, called "qiviut" lets them brave the northern winter's fiercest conditions. In fact, qiviut is 8 times warmer than cashmere! Learn about muskox survival strategies, diet, and more: http://ow.ly/1iSx30bS4x8 #Arctic

caption_original: Did you know that Canada's North is home to about 200 species of flowering plants? Despite long, harsh winters, there are brief but colourful summers. Purple saxifrage is an example of a flower that can be admired even in Parks Canada's northernmost National Park, Quttinirpaaq. Learn more about this northern jewel, which is also Nunavut's official flower! http://ow.ly/LzUV30bMDYI
